\hypertarget{question-4}{%
\subsection{Question 4}\label{question-4}}

Create a bar (aka column) chart of gender (x-axis) versus revenue
(y-axis). Omit missing values, i.e., where gender is NA or missing. Use
the plot() function rather than functions from ggplot2. Show only the
chart and not the code that generated it. Add markdown text to comment
on what the chart means.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{customer\_data }\OtherTok{=} \FunctionTok{read.csv}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{url}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"http://artificium.us/assignments/55.data{-}analytics/a{-}55{-}103/customertxndata.csv"}\NormalTok{))}
\FunctionTok{str}\NormalTok{(customer\_data)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## 'data.frame':    22800 obs. of  5 variables:
##  $ numvisits: int  7 20 22 24 1 13 23 14 11 24 ...
##  $ numtxns  : int  0 1 1 2 0 1 2 1 1 2 ...
##  $ OS       : chr  "Android" "iOS" "iOS" "iOS" ...
##  $ gender   : chr  "Male" NA "Female" "Female" ...
##  $ rev      : num  0 577 850 1050 0 ...
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{customer\_data }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{na.omit}\NormalTok{(customer\_data)}

\NormalTok{customer\_data.agg }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{aggregate}\NormalTok{(customer\_data}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{rev, }\FunctionTok{list}\NormalTok{(customer\_data}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{gender), }\AttributeTok{FUN=}\NormalTok{mean)}

\FunctionTok{barplot}\NormalTok{(customer\_data.agg}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{x,}
        \AttributeTok{main =} \StringTok{"Revenue vs gender"}\NormalTok{,}
        \AttributeTok{xlab =} \StringTok{"Gender"}\NormalTok{,}
        \AttributeTok{ylab =} \StringTok{"Revenue (US$)"}\NormalTok{,}
        \AttributeTok{names.arg =} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Male"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Female"}\NormalTok{),}
        \AttributeTok{col =} \StringTok{"navy"}\NormalTok{,}
        \AttributeTok{horiz =} \ConstantTok{FALSE}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\includegraphics{Module2_First-Steps-in-Data-Analytics-with-R_files/figure-latex/Q4-1.pdf}

The bar chart indicates that in ``male'' customers the revenue was
double compared to ``female''.

\begin{Shaded}

\CommentTok{\# Number of visits}

\CommentTok{\# Revenue }

indicates a moderate positive relationship between the number of visits
and the revenue.
